{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4f29f804-1ab7-41c3-b0f0-2937d75e5f79","content":"The template is **structurally valid** but has a few issues before it's NuGet-ready:\n\n### Problems\n\n1. **Missing `description`** — NuGet gallery needs this for discoverability. Add a top-level `\"description\"` field.\n\n2. **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — Users can select a framework, but the value won't be substituted into your `.csproj`. You need something like:\n   ```json\n   \"replaces\": \"net9.0\"\n   ```\n\n3. **No `$schema`** — Not required, but strongly recommended for validation/IntelliSense:\n   ```\n   \"https://json.schemastore.org/template\"\n   ```\n\n4. **No `groupIdentity`** — Recommended when publishing to NuGet so multiple versions of the same template are grouped properly.\n\n5. **No `preferNameDirectory`** — Typically `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n\n### Looks Good\n\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all correctly defined.\n\n**Verdict:** Not quite ready — at minimum add `description` and fix the `Framework` symbol's `replaces` so the parameter actually works.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b395bab3-80af-4219-907a-918b32258ebc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can spot:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but recommended for validation/IntelliSense.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet templates so multiple versions/variants can be grouped.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple template versions coexist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but often set for project templates.\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0` but the `Framework` symbol doesn't use `replaces`** — The symbol won't actually replace anything in the project file unless there's a `replaces` property or the symbol name matches a source replacement.\n\n\n6. **Missing `description`** — Not required but highly recommended for NuGet gallery display.\n\nThe main concern is that the `Framework` parameter has choices defined but lacks a `replaces` property, so selecting a different framework won't actually update the `.csproj` file's `<TargetFramework>` element unless \"net9.0\" is already present in the source files.\n\nLooking at the core issues with this template: it's missing a `$schema` for tooling support, the `Framework` symbol won't substitute values without `replaces`, and it lacks `preferNameDirectory` and `groupIdentity` which are recommended best practices for project templates.","outputTokens":892},"id":"43f78774-6cf9-49c3-99fb-86435ac19fd4","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:39:13.852Z","parentId":"9338560d-b8f1-4006-93ee-28b25c532660"}
